************** G E N E R A L   I N F O R M A T I O N *************1325 1451   22
                                                                  1325 1451   23
This evaluated data file is based on a software system built      1325 1451   24
around the nuclear model code TALYS [kon23], version 2.0. It is   1325 1451   25
part of a large collection of isotopic evaluations, all created by1325 1451   26
running the system with either adjusted or default input          1325 1451   27
parameters. This means that the data in the entire collection have1325 1451   28
been tested in detail for many isotopes against individual        1325 1451   29
experimental data, while for other isotopes it is only as good as 1325 1451   30
the global quality of TALYS at the moment. The mutual quality of  1325 1451   31
all individual data files is however consistent: The same set of  1325 1451   32
nuclear models is used and, equally important, the same ENDF-6    1325 1451   33
formatting procedures for each isotope. The data file has been    1325 1451   34
created automatically using the ENDF-6 format generator TEFAL.    1325 1451   35
                                                                  1325 1451   36
The resulting data file provides a complete representation of     1325 1451   37
nuclear data needed for transport, activation, damage, heating,   1325 1451   38
radioactivity, and shielding applications over the incident       1325 1451   39
proton energy range from 0.001 to 200. MeV.                       1325 1451   40
                                                                  1325 1451   41
All transport and activation data for neutrons, charged particles,1325 1451   42
photons and residual nuclides are filed. This includes cross      1325 1451   43
sections, angular distributions, double-differential spectra,     1325 1451   44
isomeric production, discrete and continuum photon production     1325 1451   45
cross sections, residual production cross sections and recoils.   1325 1451   46
This general purpose evaluation can thus be used as both          1325 1451   47
transport and activation library.                                 1325 1451   48
                                                                  1325 1451   49
A complete set of covariance data is included, which is stored    1325 1451   50
in MF31-40.                                                       1325 1451   51
                                                                  1325 1451   52
**** N U C L I D E    S P E C I F I C   I N F O R M A T I O N ****1325 1451   53
                                                                  1325 1451   54
None                                                              1325 1451   55
                                                                  1325 1451   56
***************************** T A L Y S **************************1325 1451   57
                                                                  1325 1451   58
TALYS is a computer code system for the prediction and analysis   1325 1451   59
of nuclear reactions. TALYS simulates reactions that involve      1325 1451   60
neutrons, gamma-rays, protons, deuterons, tritons, helions and    1325 1451   61
alpha-particles, in the 1 keV - 200 MeV energy range. This is     1325 1451   62
achieved by implementing a suite of nuclear reaction models into  1325 1451   63
a single code system. This nuclear data file is based on a        1325 1451   64
theoretical analysis that utilizes the optical model, compound    1325 1451   65
nucleus statistical theory, fission, direct reactions and         1325 1451   66
pre-equilibrium processes, in combination with databases and      1325 1451   67
models for nuclear structure. The following output of TALYS is    1325 1451   68
stored in this data file:                                         1325 1451   69
                                                                  1325 1451   70
- Total, elastic and non-elastic cross sections                   1325 1451   71
- Inelastic cross sections to discrete states                     1325 1451   72
- Exclusive channel cross sections, e.g. (n,g), (n,2n), (n,np),.. 1325 1451   73
- Inelastic scattering angular distributions to discrete states   1325 1451   74
- Exclusive channel energy spectra                                1325 1451   75
- Exclusive channel double-differential spectra                   1325 1451   76
- Exclusive gamma production for discrete states and continuum    1325 1451   77
- Elastic scattering angular distributions                        1325 1451   78
- Recoil data                                                     1325 1451   79
- Total particle cross sections, e.g. (p,xn), (p,xp),..           1325 1451   80
- Total particle energy spectra                                   1325 1451   81
- Total particle double-differential spectra                      1325 1451   82
- Isomeric and ground state cross sections                        1325 1451   83
- Residual production cross sections                              1325 1451   84
                                                                  1325 1451   85
For a description of the used nuclear models and their            1325 1451   86
parameterization we refer to [kon19]. If for this specific        1325 1451   87
nuclide we deviate from the global parameterization, it is made   1325 1451   88
explicit above under Nuclide Specific Information.                1325 1451   89
                                                                  1325 1451   90
***************** F I L E   I N F O R M A T I O N ****************1325 1451   91
                                                                  1325 1451   92
##### MF1: GENERAL INFORMATION                                    1325 1451   93
                                                                  1325 1451   94
- MT451    : Descriptive data and directory                       1325 1451   95
                                                                  1325 1451   96
This text and the full directory of used MF/MT sections.          1325 1451   97
                                                                  1325 1451   98
##### MF3: REACTION CROSS SECTIONS                                1325 1451   99
                                                                  1325 1451  100
All the data present in the following MT-sections have been       1325 1451  101
calculated with TALYS, possibly normalized to experimental data.  1325 1451  102
If the maximal cross section in an excitation function over the   1325 1451  103
whole energy range does not exceed 1.e-9 b, the MT-number is not  1325 1451  104
included. Cross sections lower than 1.e-20 b are assumed to have  1325 1451  105
no physical meaning and are set to zero. All MT numbers extend up 1325 1451  106
to the highest incident energy.                                   1325 1451  107
The following reaction channels/MT numbers are generally included:1325 1451  108
                                                                  1325 1451  109
- MT2      : Elastic scattering cross section: nuclear +          1325 1451  110
             interference terms                                   1325 1451  111
                                                                  1325 1451  112
Obtained by integrating the "nuclear-plus-interference" angular   1325 1451  113
distributions of MF=6.  Note that because of the interference     1325 1451  114
effect, the tabulations in both MF=6 and MF=3 can be negative at  1325 1451  115
some energies and angles.                                         1325 1451  116
                                                                  1325 1451  117
- MT3      : Non-elastic cross section                            1325 1451  118
                                                                  1325 1451  119
Calculated with the optical model over the whole energy range.    1325 1451  120
                                                                  1325 1451  121
- MT4      : Total inelastic cross section                        1325 1451  122
                                                                  1325 1451  123
Sum of MT=51-91.                                                  1325 1451  124
                                                                  1325 1451  125
- MT5      : (p,anything) cross section                           1325 1451  126
                                                                  1325 1451  127
MT5 contains the reactions which can not be stored in any other   1325 1451  128
MT-number. The information of MF3/MT5 can be combined with        1325 1451  129
MF6/MT5 to obtain residual production cross sections particle     1325 1451  130
production cross sections and (double-)differential cross         1325 1451  131
sections.                                                         1325 1451  132
                                                                  1325 1451  133
- MT16     : (p,2n) cross section                                 1325 1451  134
- MT17     : (p,3n) cross section                                 1325 1451  135
- MT22     : (p,na) cross section                                 1325 1451  136
- MT28     : (p,np) cross section                                 1325 1451  137
- MT51-90  : (p,n') cross section for 1st-40th excited state      1325 1451  138
- MT91     : (p,n') continuum cross section                       1325 1451  139
- MT102    : (p,gamma) cross section                              1325 1451  140
- MT103    : (p,p) cross section                                  1325 1451  141
- MT104    : (p,d) cross section                                  1325 1451  142
- MT105    : (p,t) cross section                                  1325 1451  143
- MT106    : (p,h) cross section                                  1325 1451  144
- MT107    : (p,a) cross section                                  1325 1451  145
- MT600-610: (p,p) cross section for 0th-10th excited state       1325 1451  146
- MT649    : (p,p) continuum cross section                        1325 1451  147
- MT650-655: (p,d) cross section for 0th-5th excited state        1325 1451  148
- MT699    : (p,d) continuum cross section                        1325 1451  149
- MT700-705: (p,t) cross section for 0th-5th excited state        1325 1451  150
- MT749    : (p,t) continuum cross section                        1325 1451  151
- MT750-755: (p,h) cross section for 0th-5th excited state        1325 1451  152
- MT799    : (p,h) continuum cross section                        1325 1451  153
- MT800-810: (p,a) cross section for 0th-10th excited state       1325 1451  154
- MT849    : (p,a) continuum cross section                        1325 1451  155
                                                                  1325 1451  156
##### MF6: PRODUCT ENERGY-ANGLE DISTRIBUTIONS                     1325 1451  157
                                                                  1325 1451  158
In MF6 we store all secondary energy, angle, and energy-angle     1325 1451  159
distributions, as well as all residual and discrete + continuum   1325 1451  160
photon production cross sections for channels other than capture  1325 1451  161
(MT102) and reactions to discrete levels (MT51,etc.).             1325 1451  162
All data are generated with TALYS.                                1325 1451  163
                                                                  1325 1451  164
- MT5      : (p,anything) yields and energy-angle distributions   1325 1451  165
                                                                  1325 1451  166
MT5 contains, in this order,                                      1325 1451  167
For neutrons up to alpha particles and photons:                   1325 1451  168
- the production yields per particle for the whole energy range   1325 1451  169
- the secondary energy-angle distributions per particles which are1325 1451  170
  not represented by explicit MT numbers. On a secondary energy   1325 1451  171
  grid the relative emission spectra are given together with the  1325 1451  172
  parameters for the Kalbach systematics for angular              1325 1451  173
  distributions. Inelastic scattering cross sections for discrete 1325 1451  174
  states have been broadened and added to the continuum spectra.  1325 1451  175
For each residual product:                                        1325 1451  176
- the production yields for the whole energy range.               1325 1451  177
- the recoil                                                      1325 1451  178
These distributions can be multiplied with MF3/MT5 to get         1325 1451  179
the production cross sections and (double-)differential cross     1325 1451  180
sections.                                                         1325 1451  181
                                                                  1325 1451  182
- MT16     : (p,2n) energy-angle distr. and photon production     1325 1451  183
                                                                  1325 1451  184
First, for each type of outgoing particle, the (trivial) integer  1325 1451  185
particle yields are given. Next, on a sufficiently dense incident 1325 1451  186
energy grid the secondary energy-angle distributions are          1325 1451  187
specified by means of the relative emission spectra and the       1325 1451  188
parameters for the Kalbach systematics for angular distributions. 1325 1451  189
Next, the photon yield is tabulated as a function of incident     1325 1451  190
energy. For each incident energy, the photon production is given  1325 1451  191
for all discrete gamma lines present in the final nucleus. A      1325 1451  192
continuum photon distribution is added to this. We assume         1325 1451  193
isotropy for all produced gamma rays.                             1325 1451  194
                                                                  1325 1451  195
For the following MT-numbers, the same procedure as for MT16 is   1325 1451  196
followed:                                                         1325 1451  197
                                                                  1325 1451  198
- MT17 : (p,3n) energy-angle distr. and photon production         1325 1451  199
- MT22 : (p,na) energy-angle distr. and photon production         1325 1451  200
- MT28 : (p,np) energy-angle distr. and photon production         1325 1451  201
- MT91 : (p,n') continuum energy-angle distr. and phot. prod.     1325 1451  202
- MT649: (p,p) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     1325 1451  203
- MT699: (p,d) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     1325 1451  204
- MT749: (p,t) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     1325 1451  205
- MT809: (p,h) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     1325 1451  206
- MT849: (p,a) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     1325 1451  207
                                                                  1325 1451  208
##### MF8: RADIOACTIVE DECAY DATA                                 1325 1451  209
                                                                  1325 1451  210
For reactions to isomers, MF8 designates where the information    1325 1451  211
for isomeric versus ground state production, or residual          1325 1451  212
production can be found, i.e. for each MT number it points to     1325 1451  213
either MF6, MF9 or MF10.                                          1325 1451  214
                                                                  1325 1451  215
##### MF9: MULTIPLICITIES FOR PRODUCTION OF RADIOACTIVE NUCLIDES  1325 1451  216
                                                                  1325 1451  217
MF9 is used for isomer production by non-threshold reactions.     1325 1451  218
Final states with a lifetime that exceeds 1 second are treated    1325 1451  219
as isomer.                                                        1325 1451  220
                                                                  1325 1451  221
##### MF10: CROSS SECTIONS FOR PRODUCTION OF RADIOACTIVE NUCLIDES 1325 1451  222
                                                                  1325 1451  223
MF10 is used for isomer production by threshold reactions.        1325 1451  224
Final states with a lifetime that exceeds 1 second are treated    1325 1451  225
as isomer.                                                        1325 1451  226
                                                                  1325 1451  227
##### MF33: COVARIANCES OF NEUTRON CROSS SECTIONS                 1325 1451  228
                                                                  1325 1451  229
In MF33, we store the covariances of most, but not all, reaction  1325 1451  230
channels that are given in MF3. All covariances are generated     1325 1451  231
with the TASMAN code [kon19], which generates TALYS runs using    1325 1451  232
a Monte Carlo parameter method.                                   1325 1451  233
For each MT-number, the information consists of:                  1325 1451  234
1. Covariances for MTa, Ea and MTa, Ea (variances)                1325 1451  235
2. Covariances for MTa, Ea and MTa, Eb (correlations for the      1325 1451  236
   same reaction channel between different energies)              1325 1451  237
3. Covariances for MTa, Ea and MTb, Ea (correlations between      1325 1451  238
   different reaction channels for the same energy)               1325 1451  239
4. Covariances for MTa, Ea and MTb, Eb (correlations between      1325 1451  240
   different reaction channels for different energies)            1325 1451  241
Classes 1 and 2 are covered by NI-type subsubsections with        1325 1451  242
flag LB=5, followed by a LB=8 section which contains              1325 1451  243
the cross section variances multiplied by 1.e-3. Next, classes 3  1325 1451  244
and 4 are covered by flag LB=6 to account for the different       1325 1451  245
energy grids that two correlating MT-sections may have. Since     1325 1451  246
the total correlation matrix is fully symmetric, we only need to  1325 1451  247
include the correlation elements between different MT-numbers     1325 1451  248
once, and we do that in the subsection with the lowest of the     1325 1451  249
two MT-numbers. We include covariance information for all the     1325 1451  250
total cross sections, the lumped partial cross sections and the   1325 1451  251
individual inelastic cross sections per level (MT51,...). We do   1325 1451  252
not include covariances for MT600 and higher MT-numbers. For the  1325 1451  253
most important channels, we include cross-channel correlations.   1325 1451  254
                                                                  1325 1451  255
##### MF40: COVARIANCES OF ISOMER PRODUCTION                      1325 1451  256
                                                                  1325 1451  257
For covariances of ground state and isomeric cross sections, the  1325 1451  258
same procedures as for MF33 are used.                             1325 1451  259
                                                                  1325 1451  260
